Packages to be installed: copula, evd, ismev, maps. You can install a package by install.packages("copula") etc.

The data consist of annual maxima of daily maximum temperatures for the years 19502018 for \(d = 54\) stations around Belgium. Derived from the homogenized E-OBS dataset E-OBS v19.0eHOM data, made available in the supplementary material of Auld et al.(2023).

The aim is to estimate joint probabilities of high annual temperatures - at multiple locations simultaneously (AND), - at least one location (OR).

We will compare various estimates: 1. the empirical probability 2. by applying univariate extreme-value theory (EVT) to the maximum of maxima 3. by fitting a max-stable distribution to the vector of component-wise maxima - non-parametric estimate of the Pickands dependence function - parametric estimate, via a two-stage procedure - margins estimated via fitting univariate generalized extreme-value (GEV) distributions - margins estimated via the empirical cumulative distribution function (cdf)

2 Empirical probability

We are interested in probabilities of the type \[\begin{align*} &\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > u_i \text{ and } M_j > u_j) & &\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_1 > u_1 \text{ and } M_2 > u_2 \text{ and } M_3 > u_3) \\ &\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > u_i \text{ or } M_j > u_j) & &\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_1 > u_1 \text{ or } M_2 > u_2 \text{ or } M_3 > u_3) \end{align*}\]

Estimate the above probabilities for \(u_1 = u_2 = u_3 = 35^\circ\) by the empirical probabilities, that is, the frequency of the events in the sample. In R, the logical operators are & (AND) and | (OR).

# Here and below, it's certainly possible to write more elegant and general code, using loops etc.
u <- 35

mean((M[,1] > u) & (M[,2] > u))
## [1] 0.01449275
mean((M[,1] > u) & (M[,3] > u))
## [1] 0
mean((M[,2] > u) & (M[,3] > u))
## [1] 0.04347826
mean((M[,1] > u) | (M[,2] > u))
## [1] 0.05797101
mean((M[,1] > u) | (M[,3] > u))
## [1] 0.07246377
mean((M[,2] > u) | (M[,3] > u))
## [1] 0.07246377
mean((M[,1] > u) & (M[,2] > u) & (M[,3] > u)) 
## [1] 0
mean((M[,1] > u) | (M[,2] > u) | (M[,3] > u)) 
## [1] 0.07246377

3 Univariate EVT applied to the maximum of the maxima

For each year, extract the maximum of the maxima at two or three locations. Use the function pmax(). For our three cities, this gives four series of maxima (three pairs and one triple).

M12 <- pmax(M[,1], M[,2])
M13 <- pmax(M[,1], M[,3])
M23 <- pmax(M[,2], M[,3])

M123 <- pmax(M[,1], M[,2], M[,3])

Fit a univariate GEV distribution to each of the series, by the function gev.fit() in ismev.

For the OR version, calculate the probabilities by the GEV fit. To do so, use \[ \operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > u \text{ or } M_j > u) = \operatorname{\mathsf{P}}[\max(M_i, M_j) > u]. \] The GEV cumulative distribution function is implemented in pgev() of the package evd.

library(evd)
p.or.12 <- pgev(q = u, loc = gev12[1], scale = gev12[2], shape = gev12[3], lower.tail = FALSE)
p.or.13 <- pgev(q = u, loc = gev13[1], scale = gev13[2], shape = gev13[3], lower.tail = FALSE)

p.or.123 <- pgev(q = u, loc = gev123[1], scale = gev123[2], shape = gev123[3], lower.tail = FALSE)

4 Nonparametric estimation of a max-stable distribution

We will estimate the Pickands dependence function non-parametrically and then combine the estimated dependence structure with the parametric GEV margins to estimate the multivariate excess probabilities. For simplicity, we will limit ourselves to the bivariate case.

4.0.1 Estimation and visualization of the Pickands dependence function

For each of the three pairs of cities, make a graph of the Capra-Fougres-Genest estimator \(\hat{\Pidf}\) of the Pickands dependence function \(\Pidf\).

Use the function An.biv() of the package copula to compute the estimate and use curve to make the plot.

For each pair, also compute an estimate of the dependence coefficient \(\chi\). To do so, put \[ \hat{\chi} = 2 \left\{1 - \hat{\Pidf}(0.5)\right\}. \] Do you notice a link between the value of \(\hat{\chi}\) and the distance between the cities? Optionally: visualize \(\hat{\chi}\) on the plot of \(\hat{\Pidf}\).

library(copula)
for (i in (1:2)) {
  for (j in (i+1):3) {
    curve(An.biv(M[,c(i,j)], x, estimator = "CFG"),
          xlab = "w", ylab = "A(w)",
          main = paste("Pickands dependence function A,", 
                       cities$name[i], "vs", cities$name[j]),
          ylim = c(0.5,1),
          col = "blue", lwd = 2)
    lines(c(0, 0.5, 1), c(1,0.5,1), col = "gray")
    lines(c(0,1),c(1,1), col = "gray")
    Ahalf <- An.biv(M[,c(i,j)], w=0.5)
    lines(c(0.5,0.5), c(1, Ahalf), lty = "dotted", lwd = 2)
    text(x = 0.5, y = (Ahalf+1)/2, 
         labels = paste("chi = 2{1-A(.5)} =", round(2*(1-Ahalf),3)),
         pos = 4
         )
  }
}

Interpret the value of \(\hat{\chi}\) in terms of the locations of the cities.

4.1 Estimation of the joint excess probability

For a bivariate max-stable distribution function \(G\) with margins \(G_1\) and \(G_2\) and Pickands dependence function \(\Pidf\), we have \[ G(x_1,x_2) = (u_1u_2)^{\Pidf(w)}, \qquad \left\{ \begin{array}{@{}r{\;=\;}l} u_1 & G_1(x_1) \\ u_2 & G_2(x_2) \\ w & \log(u_2) / \log(u_1 u_2) \end{array} \right. \] For a pair of cities of your choice, combine the estimates of the marginal (non-)excess probabilities and the estimate of the Pickands dependence function to obtain the required excess probabilities. Note that, for the pair \((i, j)\), say, we have \[\begin{align*} \operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > x \text{ or } M_j > x) &= 1 - G_{ij}(x,x) \\ \operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > x \text{ and } M_j > x) &= \operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > x) + \operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_j > x) - \operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > x \text{ or } M_j > x). \end{align*}\]

(G1 <- pgev(q = u, loc = gev1[1], scale = gev1[2], shape = gev1[3], lower.tail = TRUE))
## [1] 0.9749493
(G2 <- pgev(q = u, loc = gev2[1], scale = gev2[2], shape = gev2[3], lower.tail = TRUE))
## [1] 0.9317289
(G3 <- pgev(q = u, loc = gev3[1], scale = gev3[2], shape = gev3[3], lower.tail = TRUE))
## [1] 0.9257452
(A12 <- An.biv(x = M[,c(1,2)], w = log(G2)/log(G1*G2), estimator = "CFG"))
## [1] 0.7598188
(p.or.12.Pick <- 1-(G1*G2)^A12)
## [1] 0.07040457
(p.and.12.Pick <- p1+p2-p.or.12.Pick)
## [1] 0.02291721
(A13 <- An.biv(x = M[,c(1,3)], w = log(G3)/log(G1*G3), estimator = "CFG"))
## [1] 0.7975742
(p.or.13.Pick <- 1-(G1*G3)^A13)
## [1] 0.07851811
(p.and.13.Pick <- p1+p3-p.or.13.Pick)
## [1] 0.02078741
(A23 <- An.biv(x = M[,c(2,3)], w = log(G3)/log(G2*G3), estimator = "CFG"))
## [1] 0.6199258
(p.or.23.Pick <- 1-(G2*G3)^A23)
## [1] 0.08759216
(p.and.23.Pick <- p2+p3-p.or.23.Pick)
## [1] 0.05493374

Compare the probabilities with the one of the previous approaches.

5 Parametric modelling of a max-stable distribution

Now lets assume the bivariate GEV distribution to a parametric family. We will first estimate the parameters by maximum likelihood and then compute the multivariate excess probabilities of interest in the fitted parametric model.

For the marginal GEV parameters, we have two choices: - estimate the parameters jointly with the dependence parameter; - use a two-stage procedure: in a first stage, we fit the marginal GEV parameters separately to each margin; in a second stage, we fix the marginal parameters and estimate the dependence parameter.

(A third option would be to use the pseudo-likelihood procedure, estimating the margins nonparametrically with the empirical cdf.)

For the parametric estimate, we will use the function fbvevd() from the package evd. To evaluate probabilities under the fitted model, use the function pmvevd() from the same package; alternatively, use the function pCopula() from the copula package, knowing that the logistic model in EVT is actually the same as the Gumbel copula. Recall that the link between a bivariate cdf \(G\) and its margins \(G_1, G_2\) is given by \[ G(x_1,x_2) = C \left(G_1(x_1), G_2(x_2)\right) \] where \(C\) is the copula of \(G\).

5.1 Joint parameter estimation

Fit the bivariate GEV with the logistic dependence model, estimating all parameters jointly.

library(evd)
res12 <- fbvevd(x = M[,c(1,2)],
                model = "log")$estimate

Estimate the probabilities \(\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > u)\), \(\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_j > u)\), \(\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > u \text{ or } M_j > u)\) and \(\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > u \text{ and } M_j > u)\). Use the functions pgev() for the marginal ones and pmvevd() for the joint one \(\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i \le u \text{ and } M_j \le u)\), the bivariate distribution function.

(G1 <- pgev(q = u, loc = res12[1], scale = res12[2], shape = res12[3]))
##    shape1 
## 0.9501467
(G2 <- pgev(q = u, loc = res12[4], scale = res12[5], shape = res12[6]))
##    shape2 
## 0.9082471
(G12 <- pmvevd(q = c(u, u),
               dep = res12[7],
               d = 2,
               mar = list(res12[1:3], res12[4:6]),
               model = "log"))
##       dep 
## 0.9011762
(p.or.12.log <- 1-G12)
##        dep 
## 0.09882378
(p1 <- 1-G1)
##     shape1 
## 0.04985327
(p2 <- 1-G2)
##     shape2 
## 0.09175293
(p.and.12.log <- p1+p2-p.or.12.log)
##     shape1 
## 0.04278242

res12 <- fbvevd(x = M[,c(1,2)],
                loc1 = gev.par1[1],
                scale1 = gev.par1[2],
                shape1 = gev.par1[3],
                loc2 = gev.par2[1],
                scale2 = gev.par2[2],
                shape2 = gev.par2[3],
                model = "log")$estimate

Estimate the probabilities \(\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > u)\), \(\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_j > u)\), \(\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > u \text{ or } M_j > u)\) and \(\operatorname{\mathsf{P}}(M_i > u \text{ and } M_j > u)\).

(G1 <- pgev(q = u, loc = gev.par1[1], scale = gev.par1[2], shape = gev.par1[3]))
